{"id":14881823,"mediaExerciseId":"1154ebb9-0851-461e-af29-396ed284c249","exerciseName":"7","chapterName":"23","chapterTitle":"Enterprise Risk Management","groupId":612487,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":786,"solutions":[{"id":6004740,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will discuss the similarities of call options and bond options when done using bonds and interest rates. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A put option and a call option are two opposite things. In a put option, the buyer of the contract has the right, but not the obligation, to sell the product. On the other hand, a call option gives the buyer of the contract the right, but not the obligation, to buy the product.\n\nThis is why a put option on a bond is practically the same as a call option on an interest rate since the price of the bond moves in the opposite direction of the interest rate which is similar to the movement supported by the option. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":254,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/9e937f39bf6311948a898c1c5bf98309/4b8edf827dee697b01299402f0af688d/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/9e937f39bf6311948a898c1c5bf98309/4b8edf827dee697b01299402f0af688d/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"9911cc0b-8e8f-4a15-a2c8-fba3d3d89262","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchl